// help.grif - GRIF format
01 How To Use EditGrif
	EditGrif is an editor for GRIF game files. It handles some of the organizing, gives helpful information, and does script validation.\n\nCreate a new GRIF file or open an existing one. You can also open a GrifStack file (*.grifstack) containing a list of GRIF filenames for editing a complete game.\n\nThe various tabs such as "Rooms" and "Values" will fill in with the proper information. You can then add or edit information on those tabs.\n\nThe Start, Rooms, and Items tabs are specialized for those kinds of key/values. The others only consist of a list of keys and a text box for values. Selecting a key will show the current value for that key. Adding a key will add it to the list and allow a value to be typed.\n\nThe Help tab is not editable, but includes the help topics for EditGrif and all built-in DAGS functions and identifiers. DAGS is the scripting language used in GRIF games.
02 GRIF Files
	GRIF files (*.grif) are list of key/value pairs. These make up the data and scripts for running a game.\n\nKeys are strings. They cannot be blank or null or just have whitespace. They also cannot start or end with whitespace. There are a few characters not allowed in keys, such as a backslash (\) or double quote ("). Keys cannot start with an underline (_) as that is reserved for local script variables.\n\nKeys are usually in several parts separated by periods (.). For example, "room.kitchen.exit.east" would be the key for the east exit from the kitchen. It might have a new room name, or a message to display, or a script to run.\n\nEditGrif has list boxes for the rooms and items, and other list boxes for the room exits, room values, and item values. It will create the correct keys for those and some others.\n\nFunction keys start with an at sign (@) followed by a function name. If the function has any parameters, they will be in parenthesis with commas in between. For example, "@currentroom", "@goto(roomname)", "@switch(x,y)" are all valid functions keys.\n\nValues can be anything, including empty strings (""). They can be scripts starting with "@", or text values. They can be the special value "null", which means no value exists.\n\nScript values will be saved in GRIF files as formatted strings across several lines with proper indenting.\n\nGRIF files can also be saved in JSON format if desired. These start with "{", end with "}", and have proper JSON keys and values in quotes within. Scripts are not formatted in JSON files but compacted into long strings.
